  "id": "",
  "summary": "nolimit-x ships heavily obfuscated payload with child_process + HTTP POST exfiltration shape",
  "details": "The package contains a hidden `.ad/` directory with 40+ heavily obfuscated JavaScript files using hex-mangled identifiers (`_0x...`) characteristic of automated obfuscators used to hide malicious behavior. One of these files, `.ad/x0.js`, combines `require('child_process')` with HTTP `POST` and host identification primitives (`hostname`, `id`) — the canonical fingerprint of a credential/host exfiltration or remote-execution component. Other files in the same directory have purpose-suggestive names (`phone-validator.js`, `sms-providers.js`, `smtp-health-cache.js`, `web-command.js`, `from-generator.js`) consistent with abuse tooling (SMS/SMTP fraud, command-and-control), all opaque under obfuscation. There is no legitimate reason for a public npm package to ship dozens of obfuscated modules in a hidden dotfile directory; obfuscation at this scale combined with child_process+POST+hostname collection meets the unambiguous attack-fingerprint criteria. Installers pulling this package expose their hosts to whatever code paths the bundled `.ad/` modules invoke.",
